                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d736">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00111A Arms Control–Transshipments/13:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-09-25T14:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 25, 1939—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 25—8:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1810. My 1670, September 15, 9 p.m.<note n="78" xml:id="d736fn78">Not
                        printed.</note> Following informal letter dated September 23 received from
                    the Foreign Office: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“I write to assure you that His Majesty’s Government will do nothing to
                            impede the progress of transmission to China of arms and materials for
                            the Chinese Government exported from the United States, provided that
                            the documents of the ships in which they are carried clearly indicate
                            their destination.<note n="79" xml:id="d736fn79">In telegram No. 2087,
                                October 19, 11 a.m., the Ambassador reported a similar assurance
                                from the British Foreign Office regarding shipments of arms to the
                                Liberian Government, Thailand, and the Shanghai International
                                Settlement Municipal Police.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>2. You will, of course, understand that in present circumstances it is
                            possible that these ships will be stopped in order that their identity
                            may be established and their papers examined. If, however, this
                            examination proves satisfactory they will naturally be allowed to
                            proceed at once without further hindrance.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennedy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
